I’m honestly not into Oracle decks at all but when I saw that @alewis.art was creating one I had to get in on that action. 

I backed this beautiful deck on Kickstarter back in 2019, but due to covid the production of it was hugely delayed - I really felt for her! 

But the deck is finally here! Thank you for your beautiful work on this deck Annabelle, you’ve done an outstanding job and I can’t wait to use them! 

#witchesoflegend #witchesoflegendoracledeck #unboxing #oracledecks #indieoracledeck #oracledecksofinstagram #witchesofinstagram🔮🌙

node.text:
I was honoured to be asked to be a part of this Cauldron Spell video organised by @michellemarielliott. Michelle has been running a global intention spell every week for the last few years, if you would like to join check out the FB group Cauldron of Change or Michelle’s website www.WytchWyse.com
•
Thank you to all supporters of my Cauldron spell who took part and helped to create this wonderful video. We are all magical practitioners who follow our own Paths and are deeply rooted to our Earth Mother and along with many others from across the world who have come together in the Cauldron of Changes to focus each week for positive change.  In the midst of all this chaos in the world our heart magic strongly shines out to you all, let's shine together to being about a much needed change and respect in all people, for one another and for the flora a d fauna of our Blessed Earth.  This is our strong will and intent.  So it is!  Blessed Be xxx

Thoughts are with all those affected by the tragic event in Plymouth last week. Only an hour or so before this happened I had been talking with @witchofthewilde about how fortunate we are to not experience gun violence in the U.K., it seems so unimaginable these days. I can only hope this highlights the problems of incel culture so that society as a whole can address them before more incidents like this take place. 

#plymouthtogether 

💚💚💚💚💚

node.text:
Today’s new moon in Leo is happening on something called the lions gate portal, which happens every year on August 8th. It is supposed to be a great time for intention setting, spiritual clear outs, and spell work, but listen - if you can’t be arsed that’s ok. You’re not going to miss out on the golden opportunity of a lifetime if you give it a miss. 

It’s been an exceptionally challenging time for many people, the vast majority of us have been living in survival mode for over a year now and just getting to the end of the day is an achievement in itself. When life is like this, it’s very important to be careful where you put your energy. 

So this new moon if you just can’t find the energy for intricate spells, lengthy rituals, and intense manifestations, just give yourself the gift of not giving a fuck. 

Hope you have the new moon you need!

If you are in the US please text PUGZCE to 50409 or to @resistbot on Twitter to #stopline3

Fires have been raging through Greece and Turkey for 10 days now, decimating homes, infrastructure, wildlife, and the ecosystem. 

Thousands of people have been evacuated from their homes, many have lost their lives and it appears that with strong winds and searing temperatures forecast, there is worse yet to come. 

Last year the witch community did a truly beautiful thing and United to donate money and conduct rain spells for the wildfires that raged through Australia. It’s time to do that again.

This new moon let us come together and use our collective intent to quench these scorched lands and end the death and devastation ripping through the countries. 

If you need inspiration for spellwork I will be posting a simple rain spell that you can do every day. If you want to get involved that would be amazing, the more of us that do this, the better. 

Donate to:

Turkey 2021 Wildfire Relief Fund (@turkishphilanthropyfunds)

Mugwort harvest. I’ve tried to grow this several times but I always end up having to forage it from the side of the road. Not exactly ideal but needs must! 

Mugwort is a great anti inflammatory and the Romans were said to break off pieces of the plant and stuff them in their shoes to alleviate fatigue and sore feet. 

It’s often said that mugwort makes itself known to you when you are ready for it. And once it’s introduced itself to you, you can’t help but see it all over the place. Most of the time I see it as we are flying down the motorway, it’s silvery spires swaying in the summery breeze. I just wish it would grow in less dangerous spots!

node.text:
Rowan berries are out in Devon! The rowan tree is one of my most favourite to work with.

In Britain folklore the rowan has a history of being a tree of protection and as a result has long been associated with witches.

The physical characteristics of the tree may have contributed to its protective reputation. Each berry has a tiny five pointed star on the bottom, and as we know the pentagram is an ancient protective symbol.

People also believed the colour red was the best protection against magic. An old rhyme hints alludes to this: “Rowan tree and red thread / make the witches tine (meaning ‘to lose’) their speed”. Along with hawthorn and elder, rowan is known as a faerie tree.

This charm, combined with the protective qualities of a hagstone, is great for protecting the home. Hang over thresholds, chimneys, or windows for protection during the colder months. Then burn the dried berries next year as an offering and replace with fresh ones. 

I’ll be making another charm with the sticks tomorrow.

The summer cross quarter is nearly upon us! 

The first of the three harvest festivals, Lughnasadh or Lammas marks the beginning of the descent into the darker half of the year and is a good time to start taking stock of the magic you have manifested so far this year. 

It’s a bittersweet time for me as I love the summer months with a passion, and this year I don’t feel quite ready to let them go yet. 

As the reaper sacrifices John Barleycorn in the fields, so the cycle of life continues and the wheel turns. 

____________________________________

Interested in learning more about John Barleycorn and the magic associated with the Summer Cross Quarter sabbat? @megrosenbriar and I wrote a beginner-friendly guide for that! Head over to the @witch.with.me bio to find out more.

Gathering mugwort on the full moon. The silvery leaves of mugwort or Artemisia vulgaris are so strongly associated with the moon that the plant was named after the lunar goddess Artemis. 

It has a wide range of healing and magical properties, but I’m mainly using it for it’s ability to ease cramps as my cycle has shifted to the full moon. It can be used in teas, tinctures, or smoked.

Please note that this herb is not to be used by pregnant people or those looking to conceive.

node.text:
I’ve been instinctively harvesting nettle seeds all week and for very good reason. Nettle is the perfect medicine for combating stress and adrenal burn out. They are also great for skin and hair, and for supporting the kidneys. They are adaptogens ie they help you adapt to stress, and are loaded with minerals and trace elements.

They have a stimulating effect so a teaspoonful a day is a good dose, working up to a tablespoonful when you know you can handle that much.

Remember to be respectful to the plants, only take what you need and leave enough for them to re-seed.
